external_knowledge:
- Ongoing or finished complaint statuses refer to 'In Progress' and 'Completed' statuses;
- Usernames starting with "alice" are considered to match any username that begins with those letters;
- More than ten times indicates a count of complaints exceeding 10.

- "storms" metaphorically refers to complaints;
- "brewing" indicates the complaints are developing or are being managed;
- "under the Construction department's watch" means complaints are assigned to the Construction department;
- "severities" are metaphorically referred to as the priority levels of the complaints (High or Medium);
- "categories" are types of complaints (e.g., Construction, Land Use Violation);
- "raging" and "moderately turbulent" are metaphors for High and Medium priority levels, respectively.

sql:
SELECT complaint_id, description
FROM complaints
WHERE status_current = 'Completed';

SELECT DISTINCT reported_by_user_id 
FROM complaints 
WHERE assigned_department_id IS NOT NULL;

SELECT * 
FROM inspection_records 
WHERE inspection_date >= date('now','-1 month');

external_knowledge:
- 'cases' refers to complaints;
- 'team responsible for department 50' refers to complaints assigned to department with ID 50;
- 'who was in charge' refers to the inspectors handling those complaints;
- 'how it all turned out' refers to the resolution status and description of the complaints;
- 'details' include the complaint ID, record type, description, open date, department name, inspector name, status, resolution date, and resolution description.

- "blossoms" metaphorically represents complaints;
- "garden" represents the system of handling complaints;
- "gardeners" represent the departments responsible for handling complaints;
- "flowers" represent the categories of complaints;
- "bloomed fully" refers to complaints with a "Completed" status;
- "in the process of blooming" refers to complaints with an "In Progress" status.

sql:
SELECT category_id, COUNT(complaint_id) AS total_complaints
FROM complaint_category_mapping
GROUP BY category_id;
